{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474136"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11817"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.01,0.87,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32165"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3745"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12398"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy is brought to the General Practice clinic by his mother with a five-month history of increasingly sporadic vomiting, reduced energy affecting playtime, poor concentration, anorexia, malaise and hyperirritability. His mother states this is unlike him as he is usually cheerful, energetic and attentive to what she says. He has no significant medical history, apart from croup last winter. He is up to date with immunisations and does not take any regular medications. His mother states that his symptoms have only appeared since they moved house and started renovating five months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A full blood count shows microcytic anaemia with haemoglobin 90 g/L (115-140). On peripheral blood smear, there is basophilic stippling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thalassaemia","Vitamin B12 deficiency","Lead poisoning","Iron deficiency anaemia","Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of chronic \u003Cstrong\u003Elead poisoning\u003C/strong\u003E. There are multiple potential exposure sites including household lead-based paint, occupational exposure and food that has been grown with lead-rich soil. It can lead to neurological, neuromuscular and gastrointestinal symptoms such as impaired cognition, change in behaviour, impaired hearing, nausea, abdominal pain, depression and paraesthesia; with severe lead poisoning resulting in encephalopathy, coma, seizure and even death. Lead poisoning is further supported by evidence of erythrocyte basophilic stippling on peripheral blood smear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalassaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a microcytic anaemia and often is discovered in early childhood. Its presentation varies widely depending on the type and severity. Peripheral blood smear can show anisocytosis and poikilocytosis, target cells and Heinz bodies, but basophilic stippling would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a macrocytic anaemia rather than microcytic anaemia. It can also cause neurological symptoms in children such as irritability, apathy, and developmental delay. The peripheral blood smear may show hypersegmented neutrophils.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of microcytic anaemia in children. However, it would not explain the neurological symptoms or basophilic stippling seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked recessive disorder that can cause episodic haemolytic anaemia triggered by certain medications, foods, or infections. The peripheral blood smear may show Heinz bodies and bite cells. Basophilic stippling would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ingestion is the primary route of lead foreign body exposure in children.","Lead poisoning can cause neurological, neuromuscular and gastrointestinal symptoms.","Basophilic stippling on peripheral blood smear is suggestive of lead poisoning."],"references":["Suita S, Ohgami H, Nagasaki A, Yakabe S. Management of pediatric patients who have swallowed foreign objects. Am Surg 1989; 55 (9): 585-90. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2774368/","Zamani A, Kazerooni ES, Kasaee SS, Anbardar MH, Mohammadzadeh S, Shekarkhar G, Soleimani N. And the Oscar Goes to Peripheral Blood Film for the Detection of Lead Poisoning in a Complicated Toxic Patient: A Case Report with a Review of Laboratory Clues. Case Rep Med. 2022 Feb 23;2022:9238544. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35251184/","Bajwa H, Basit H. Thalassemia. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545151/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32165"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32165"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-23T19:48:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T08:16:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https:/